Peel and grate the @garlic cloves{2} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Heat a large #frying pan{} on medium-high heat (no oil).

Once hot, add the @British beef mince{240%g}. Fry until the mince has browned,
~{5-6%minutes}. Use a spoon to break it up as it cooks.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw mince.

Meanwhile, grate the @mature Cheddar cheese{30%g}.

Cut the @medium tomato{1} into 2cm chunks.

In a large #bowl{}, add the tomato chunks with a drizzle of @olive oil{drizzle}.
Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}, toss to coat, then set aside.

Once the mince has browned, drain and discard any excess fat. Add the
@tomato puree{30%g} and garlic to the frying pan. Cook for ~{1%minute}.

Stir in the @mixed herbs{1%sachet}, @red wine stock paste{28%g},
@tomato ketchup{2%tbsp} and @water{100%ml} for the sauce.

Bring to the boil, then lower the heat and simmer until thickened,
~{4-5%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: The mince is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

Meanwhile, halve the @ciabatta{2}.

Toast the ciabatta halves in your #toaster{} until golden.

Once toasted, drizzle with @olive oil{drizzle}.

Stir the @butter{20%g} through the sauce until melted.

Taste and season with @salt{} and @pepper{} if needed. Add a splash of water
if it's a little too thick. Remove from the heat.

When everything's nearly ready, add the @baby leaf mix{50%g} to the tomato
bowl. Toss to combine.

Share the ciabatta bases between your plates.

Top with the sloppy Joe sauce and sprinkle over the cheese. Sandwich shut with
the lids.

Serve your salad alongside and drizzle over the @balsamic glaze{12%ml}.

Enjoy!